  <title translate="true">Package Browser Globals Pane_Summary</title>
  <body>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">The </text><text styleclass="Program Feature" translate="true">Globals Pane </text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">display a list of any </text><link displaytype="text" defaultstyle="true" type="topiclink" href="glossglobal" styleclass="Normal" translate="true">globals</link><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> that are owned by the currently selected package.</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">Globals are typically objects like </text><text styleclass="Class Name" translate="true">PoolConstantDictionary</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">s. Although classes are strictly globals, from the point of view of the </text><text styleclass="Program Feature" translate="true">Package Browser</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> we don&apos;t count them as such since they are handled separately by the packaging system. When you add a new global object into </text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">Smalltalk</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> it is not initially assigned to any package. In the same manner as for classes, such globals are called </text><link displaytype="text" defaultstyle="true" type="topiclink" href="glossuncommittedglobals" styleclass="Normal" translate="true">uncommitted globals</link><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">. Use the </text><text styleclass="Menu Command" translate="true">Package/Add Uncommitted/Global</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> menu command to add uncommitted globals to a package. This brings up a list of all of the existing uncommitted globals in the image. Using this dialog you can add multiple globals to a package in one operation.</text></para>
  </body>
